result.execSummary:
The defendant Latoya N Price was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Retail Theft - Intentionally Take (<=$500), a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 943.50(1m)(b).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Latoya N Price in court with attorney Robert J Hampton.  Defendant Latoya N Price in custody.  Joy Hammond appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Deputy Court Clerk: KAR.
Case calendared for plea and sentencing.  State advised the Court they have complied with the Victims' Rights Law.  Offer placed on the record by the state.

AS TO COUNT 1: Defendant changes his plea to GUILTY.  Defendant examined as to his plea, advised of his Constitutional rights and the maximum penalty.  Court found that defendant knowingly, voluntarily and intelligently waived his rights.  Guilty Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights, Addendum and Elements, received and filed.  Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's plea.  Court found defendant guilty and ordered a judgment of conviction be entered on the record.  Defendant advised that if not a United States citizen, deportation is possible.

Sentencing proceeded.  Statements by the state, defense and defendant.

AS TO COUNT 1: The Court ordered defendant to serve 60 days in the House of Correction, consecutive to case #16CM1663 and her current probation revocation, with credit for 10 days time served.  The Court granted Huber privileges, pursuant to 303.08 Wis. Stats. for work and treatment.

Court ordered defendant to pay all applicable court costs and fees FORTHWITH or to be docketed as a civil judgment.

Court ordered defendant to submit a DNA sample and pay the DNA surcharge.
